Split a continuous variable into a categorial variable¶

In [8]:
def binning(var):
    train_df[var + '_bin'] = pd.qcut(train_df[var],10,duplicates='drop').values.add_categories("NoData")
    train_df[var + '_bin'] = train_df[var + '_bin'].fillna("NoData").astype(str)
    train_df[var + '_bin'].value_counts(dropna=False)
    
to_bin_features = ['AP003', 'AP008', 'CR009', 'CR015', 'CR019', 'PA022', 'PA023', 'PA029', 'TD001', 'TD005', 'TD006', 'TD009', 'TD010', 'TD014']
for i in to_bin_features:
    binning(i)
 
features_bin = [f + '_bin' for f in to_bin_features]

In [9]:
def apply_binning(var, bins):
    test_df[var + '_bin'] = pd.cut(test_df[var], bins=bins, include_lowest=True, duplicates='drop').astype(str)
    test_df[var + '_bin'] = test_df[var + '_bin'].fillna("NoData")

to_bin_features = ['AP003', 'AP008', 'CR009', 'CR015', 'CR019', 'PA022', 'PA023', 'PA029', 'TD001', 'TD005', 'TD006', 'TD009', 'TD010', 'TD014']
bins_dict = {}

# Apply binning for each feature using the bins created from training
for feature in to_bin_features:
    bins, _ = pd.qcut(train_df[feature], 10, duplicates='drop', retbins=True)
    bins = pd.Categorical(bins).categories
    bins_dict[feature] = bins
    apply_binning(feature, bins_dict[feature])

# Create the list of bin features for the testing dataset
features_bin = [f + '_bin' for f in to_bin_features]

Plot the % of Y by X¶

In [12]:
def plot_X_and_Y(var):
    import matplotlib
    import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
    import numpy as np

    z= train_df.groupby(var)['loan_default'].agg(['count','mean']).reset_index() 
    z['count_pcnt'] = z['count']/z['count'].sum()
    x = z[var]
    y_mean = z['mean']
    count_pcnt = z['count_pcnt']
    ind = np.arange(0, len(x))
    width = .5

    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(16,4))
    plt.subplot(121)
    plt.bar(ind, count_pcnt, width, color='r')
    plt.ylabel('X')
    plt.title(var + ' Distribution')
    plt.xticks(ind,x.tolist(), rotation=45)

    plt.subplot(122)
    plt.plot(ind, y_mean, width, color='b')
    plt.ylabel('Y by X')
    plt.xticks(ind,x.tolist(), rotation=45)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.title('Response mean by ' + var)
    plt.show()

Feature Engineering: weight-of-evidence (WOE) transformation¶

In [30]:
def WOE(var):
    train_df[var] = train_df[var].fillna('NoData')
    k = train_df[[var,'loan_default']].groupby(var)['loan_default'].agg(['count','sum']).reset_index()
    k.columns = [var,'Count','Good']
    k['Bad'] = k['Count'] - k['Good']
    k['Good %'] = (k['Good'] / k['Good'].sum()*100).round(2)
    k['Bad %'] = (k['Bad'] / k['Bad'].sum()*100).round(2)
    k[var+'_WOE'] = np.log(k['Good %'] / k['Bad %']).round(2)
    k = k.sort_values(by=var+'_WOE')
    return(k)

The feature transformation using Weight of Evidence (WOE) has improved the model's performance, as shown by an increase in the ROC score. The baseline model had an ROC of 0.53, while the model after WOE transformation achieved an improved ROC of 0.63. The increase in the ROC score from 0.53 to 0.63 suggests that the improved model has a better overall predictive ability and is more effective at distinguishing between default and non-default cases.
